In this extraordinarily prescient series, The Acent of Money, Professor Niall Ferguson shows how the history of money has been punctuated by gut-wrenching crises and crashes. From the origins of banks to the rise of 'Chimerica', each programme deals with a financial 'big bang' that has changed the course of history

This week; Life is a risky business which is why people take out insurance. But faced with an unexpected disaster, the state has to step in. Professor Niall Ferguson travels to post-Katrina New Orleans to ask why the free market can't provide adequate protection against catastrophe. His quest for an answer takes him to the origins of modern insurance in the early 19th century and to the birth of the welfare state in post-war Japan.    


